Drug Posession Arrests Overtime¶

Using the seaborn package, this vizualization displays Drug Posession Arrests from 2011 to 2023. In 2014, the city of Philadelphia decriminalized marijuana possession, and in 2020 at the beginning of the pandemic, the police department delayed arrests for all narcotic activity. This vizualization portays how drug arrests changed overtime as these changes in policy went into effect. We chose this specific seaborn plot because it is easier for the audience to understand how each year compares to trends from previous years.

Looking at the Changes in Drug Posession Arrests Following Marijuana Decriminalization and Arrest Deklay¶

This plot displays Drug Posession from 2011 to 2023, with vertical lines displaying when marijuana was decriminalized and when Philaelphia police delayed arrests at the start of the pandemic. This plot allows the audience to see visually when these changes took plays, and look more specifically into the possible correlation between marijuana decriminalization and drug possession arrests.

    y=alt.Y('percent_change:Q', title='Percent Change'),
    color=alt.condition(
        alt.datum.percent_change > 0,
        alt.value("steelblue"),  
        alt.value("orange") 
    )
).add_selection(brush).properties(
    width=600,
    title='Percent Change in Drug Possession Over Time' 
)

In [32]:
filtered_1823 = offensesum1823[offensesum1823['offense_category'].isin(['Burglary/Commercial', 'Burglary/Residential'])]

source = filtered_1823

chart = alt.Chart(source).mark_line().encode(
    alt.X('date:T', title='Date'),
    alt.Y('sum(count):Q', title='Sum of Arrests'),
    color=alt.Color(('offense_category'), title='Type of Offense'),
)

chart = chart + chart.transform_filter(alt.datum.offense_category == "Commercial Burglary").properties(
    width=600,
    title='Arrests for Commercial Burglary (2013-2016)'
) + chart.transform_filter(alt.datum.offense_category == "Residential Burglary").properties(
    width=600,
    title='Arrests for Residential Burglary (2013-2016)'
)

chart.display()

Summary¶

The final vizualization shows the change in Commercial Burglary and Residential Burglary between 2018 and 2023. The spike in commercial burglaries in 2020 could possibly be attributed to the Black Lives Matter protests in June of 2020. Additionally, you are able to see a spike in commercial burglaries. This could be attributed to recent lootings in Philadelphia in response to recent ocurt rulings regarding police brutality in the city of Philadelphia/ Overall, from these vizualizations, we are able to see how the greater political and social context within a municipality impacts total arrests for specific types of crime.
